UDP. The concept behind UDP is very easy since it is just a way to send out data and anyone on the network can listen to them without establishing any handshakes or anything else complex. On the sender of the data (like the exchange) we just establish a socket through socket() which creates a sock struct wrapped inside socket (general wrapper) which is wrapped inside socket_alloc with the inode for the vfs. Then after creation a socket which reserves a port, we can just start shooting data. We can do this by using sendto(fd, data, len, flags, &dest_addr, addr_len). What this does is just take an fd of the socket, data, length and destionation address (which doesn't even have to be specified) and calls ip_route_output_flow() to find the NIC through a Longest Prefix Match on the destination IP inside a hashtable.
Then it calls udp_sendmsg() which calls ip_make_skb() which creates the packet struct (sk_buff), then it goes up the network stack, gets a UDP header and an IP header and gets handed of to ip_send_skb which gives it to the send queue which puts it inside the DMA ring buffer for the target NIC after which the driver takes off. After that sendto() immediatelly returns.
That's it, there no explicit connections, no responses or anything, there is an implicit bind but thats just assigning an ephemeral port by the kernel. The reciever NIC will just create a socket (same way with socket()) then bind the socket to the correct port so we can listen to that port and the we call recvfrom(sockfd, target userspace buffer), this function looks at the sockets recieve queue and if there is something the function just copies it to the buffer. If not it goes to sleep and the same process like TCP happens. NIC recieves something, calls netif_receive_skb which calls ip_rcv which calls udp_rcv (if its ipv4 udp and to our socket of course) then it looks up the destination port from the packet in a hash table, finds our sock and appends it to the queue while waking up our thread which will then see the thing in the queue and copy it to the buffer. Next thing, and much more complex is TCP which I have already done so no need to repeat that but I did omit the actual setup and creation of the connection. I will try to explain that now.

The main thing that differentiates TCP and UDP is that TCP is birectional and requires establishing a handshake before actual data can be sent, this is done through 3 crucial messages sent between the client and the server. But before all that we need to actually make the server (like an exchange) open to making connections. We do that by creating a socket (classic way, just change to tcp), this sock it initialized with TCP_CLOSE. Then we need to bind the socket to the correct port since unlike UDP, the server also needs to listen and receive packets.
We use bind just as in UDP client. The we have to call listen which marks the socket as a receiver so it can listen to connection requests. This just changes the state from TCP_CLOSE to TCP_LISTEN and creates the listening structure. This measn creating a struct request_sock_queue which holds two queues, the SYN queue and the accept queue (actually a hashmap and a linked list respectively). These queues serve two distinct purposes and will be explained more in depth later but in short, the SYN queue holds request_sock structs that have just the bare minimum info about the client trying to establish a connection (are actively in the handshake process), these structs are very small to prevent attacks (about 64 bytes compared to 2000 bytes of all the data for a full connection) then there is the accept queue which holds and the actually made connections for accept() to retrieve at the end of the handshake, these are tcp_sock structs which fully describe it. This marks the end of the setup phase for the server. Now we need to actually make a connection (achieve the handshake).
Then we also need to do prep on the client side. This gets done the same way as client listening in UDP, we create a socket and bind it to a port. The we need to establish a connection. The connection is always initiated by the client. This is done by calling connect(sockfd, &sock_destaddr, sizeof(sockdestaddr)). This triggers the call handler sys_connect which calls inet_stream_connect(). This (for our ipv4 tcp case) will call tcp_v4_connect(params as in connect).
This will call ip_route_connect which finds the correct NIC to handle this by getting the Forwarding Information Base table and doing a LPM on the destination IP, the FIB returns a struct table which holds the net_device struct which represents the physical NIC. ip_route_connect returns that.
Then we call inet_hash_connect() which searches for an ephemeral (high free number to assign so it doesn’t hold up the actual) port and assigns it to socket in the bhash table (Bind for b).
Then we set the state of the sock with tcp_set_state(sk, TCP_SYN_SENT), this is done before anything is actually sent and can and will be reversed later if the send process goes wrong. This is done because it will lock the socket from being used by other threads which would hinder the handshake process. Next we call secure_tcp_seq to create an Initial Sequence Number and write it to the socket.
After that is done, we call tcp_connect(&sk) which will create the sk_buff (packet) struct through sk_stream_alloc_skb() and appends it to the socket tx queue.
Then calls tcp_init_nondata_skb(), this writes the headers to the allocated memory and flips SYN flag (synchronize to 1).
Then tcp_transmit_skb gets called which does the checksum and hands the packet to ip_queue_xmit which builds the IP header, looks up our NIC the table entry we received from the FIB and calls dev_queue_xmit with it that builds the final ethernet header and gives it to the NICs ring buffer.

It of course wouldn’t be possible if the server didn’t send the SYN-ACK.
When the server gets the SYN packet from the client it calls netif_receive_skb which calls ip_rcv which finds tcp_v4_rcv which calls __inet_lookup_skb which finds the serves listening socket. Since the state is set to TCP_LISTEN at this phase (no ACK yet), lookup_skb routes to tcp_v4_do_rcv which will route tcp_v4_conn_request.
This calls inet_reqsk_alloc which creates another request_sock which gets the client data+server ISN inside and then tcp_make_synack() gets called which makes a new sk_buff, sets the SYN and ACK flags to 1, the server ISN and the ACK number to client ISN+1(this is a common way to mark successful connections). This gets handed to ip_build_and_sent_pkt() which gets called instead of the normal stack since we are sending the data right back to the sender. This hands it to ip_local_out which calls ip_queue_xmit which calls dev_queue_xmit which puts it in the ring buffer. Before the end the server calls inet_csk_reqsk_queue_hash_add which adds the request_sock to the SYN queue in the server so it remembers the connections its trying to establish.
This is the last piece of the puzzle.

Then inet_csk_wait_for_connect gets called which is just a function that makes the process wait until the server responds. This gets done by putting a wait_queue_entry_t inside the sockets wait queue which points to our process. Then we call schedule_timeout() which makes the CPU remove the process from the scheduler.
This wakes up by the classic route. netif_receive_skb->ip_rcv->tcp_v4_rcv and that looks up the socket, sees TCP_SYN_SENT and passes it to tcp_rcv_state_process which reads the packet from the server which has a SYN-ACK flag inside it. This makes the function write the servers ISN to our sock and set the state to TCP_ESTABLISHED. There is a check in set_state which fires a function pointer to tcp_state_change when the state gets changed which will wake our process back up. (through looking in the wait queue of the sock and calling wake_up_interruptible, this moves it to the CPU’s run queue). We also call tcp_send_ack() which does the classic route, allocates sk_buff, fills it out and sets the ACK flag and the ACK number to server_isn+1 and pushes it onto the network stack.When the server receives the final ACK it finds the sock with __inet_lookup_skb, tcp_v4_hnd_req (the handler) gets called, this takes the IP/Port from the packet and hashes it to look in the SYN queue hash table. When it finds the correct request_sock it verifies the numbers (ISN and ACK nums) are correct and if they are, calls tcp_v4_syn_recv_sock().
This allocates the full 2000 byte sock struct with the help of sock_request data, changes the socket state to TCP_ESTABLISHED and pushes it onto the accept queue. When the server calls accept() it will receive an new fd to this exact socket, after which it gets removed from the queue. An important thing to note is that the server doesn’t actually send data to the main (like 80 in FTP) port after connecting, this is just a port the server uses to establish the connection since there can be multiple connections for the same IP, it uses the ephemeral port which is unique for each connection, this differentiates them. This marks the end of the connection establishment.
After that it does what I described in the previous document about the rx tcp stack. To make it clear, the order is 1. Setup for both 2. Client initiates connection by sending SYN 3. Server responds with SYN-ACK 4. Client responds back with ACK.
